image.altText: Man in striped suit walking down steps

props.synopsis: Justice Gregory Geason will resign as a Tasmanian Supreme Court judge after being found guilty of assault and emotional abuse, and pleading guilty to breaching a family violence order.

title.children: Judge to quit Supreme Court as 'the destruction of his public image and professional life is total'

image.altText: Composite image of six victims of jumping castle tragedy with school signage as background

props.synopsis: An engineer tells a Tasmanian court if "all eight star pickets were used" to anchor a jumping castle at the centre of a 2021 tragedy, it "would have endured the event" in which six children died.

title.children: Jumping castle would have stayed on ground if eight anchors were used, engineer tells court examining 2021 Hillcrest tragedy

image.altText: A prime minister in a suit and a female minister in a blazer standing behind him.

props.synopsis: Albanese shuffles the faces on his Tasmanian Labor team, hoping it sets him on a path to victory next federal election.

title.children: Albanese's path to victory at the next election goes through these seats

image.altText: A collection of hearing aids held in composer Rebecca Bracewell's hands.

props.synopsis: Many 26- to 65-year-olds who "fell between the cracks" when it came to accessing government assistance have turned to Sarah Dockrell and her hearing aid bank.

title.children: Meet the Tasmanian woman providing hearing aids to those in need, free of charge

image.altText: People playing pokie machines at the Cherokee Casino in Siloam Spring,

props.synopsis: The Anglican Dean of Hobart is urging the Tasmanian government not to be dissuaded from nation-leading gambling reform by pokie-owners who fear they'll lose business.

title.children: Religious leader's plea to Tasmanian government to stay the course on pokies reform

image.altText: A skate lying on the seabed.

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese heads to Tasmania to announce $28 million to improve water quality in Macquarie Harbour — the last known refuge of the endangered Maugean skate.

title.children: Federal government invests $28 million in fight to save Maugean skate

image.altText: Teddy Sheean statue with backdrop of sky and branches.

props.synopsis: Edward 'Teddy' Sheean is the first and only Australian Royal Navy Victoria Cross recipient. A life-sized statue and a naval vessel renamed in his honour mark a significant step in the long fight for recognition of the 18-year-old's deeds.

title.children: Did you miss? 📣 Teddy Sheean statue unveiled 80 years after his WWII heroics

image.altText: Donald Trump sits in court in a suit and red tie looking at the camera

props.synopsis: In the days since his election win, Donald Trump has moved to have his felony convictions in the New York hush money case dismissed, with a decision now expected next week.

title.children: 'These are unprecedented circumstances': Trump's new move to dismiss convictions

image.altText: A man in a suit looks on.

props.synopsis: In an ominous post to his 2 million followers on X, Dan Scavino uploads a GIF of sand trickling through an hourglass next to Kevin Rudd's official statement on Donald Trump's election victory.

title.children: Trump insider's cryptic message for Kevin Rudd

image.altText: A church building with a cross shrouded under branches

props.synopsis: The Catholic Church wins a High Court appeal against rulings it was vicariously liable for the actions of a priest who allegedly sexually abused a five-year-old in 1971.

title.children: Catholic Church wins High Court appeal against ruling it was vicariously liable for alleged sexual abuse by a priest

image.altText: High Court of Australia

props.synopsis: Two survivors of alleged child sex abuse win their High Court battle to sue those who placed them in care in the 50s and 60s.

title.children: Two survivors of alleged historic child sex abuse win High Court battle to sue for compensation

image.altText: A blue sign saying Queanbeyan District Health Service sits at the entrance to the carpark of a hospital

props.synopsis: An email obtained by the ABC confirms Queanbeyan Hospital has stopped providing surgical terminations for fetal anomalies and medical reasons, restricting access to a legal and time-critical form of reproductive health care.

title.children: Queanbeyan Hospital bans surgical abortions, telling local health workers the procedure 'does not currently sit within' its scope

image.altText: A hiker on top of a mountain

props.synopsis: Global emissions look to rise in 2024, a new Carbon Budget report reveals. Climate scientists say it's "grim news" because the world has the technology to change that. What's missing, they say, is political will.

title.children: The world looks set to fall 'frustratingly' short of a peak in emissions, and gas is the major driver

image.altText: A person looking at images of women in bikinis on a computer

props.synopsis: A report by Our Watch has revealed the average teenage Australian girl has viewed pornography before her 14th birthday, with fears it is becoming a default source of sexual education for children.

title.children: Young people encountering porn earlier than ever and using it for sex education, new report finds

image.altText: A phone displaying the meta logo sits on a computer keyboard

props.synopsis: This year's Shonky Awards have been announced, with Facebook parent company Meta amongst the winners for its "inadequate action" against scams.

title.children: Five companies and products make the cut as CHOICE announces 19th annual Shonky Awards

image.altText: A digital tablet is attached to a shopping trolley.

props.synopsis: Woolworths says it wants to roll out its smart shopping trolleys to more stores to help people budget their shops better. Smart carts overseas have helped increase the average customer spend by 6 per cent.

title.children: The tech company behind Woolworths 'smart' shopping trolleys says they could help you buy more impulsively

image.altText: A large truck carrying pallets of aid bundles through a dusty border crossing.

props.synopsis: The US will continue to provide military assistance to the Netanyahu government, despite aid agencies saying it has fallen short of providing enough aid to the wartorn region.

title.children: Aid agencies accuse Israel of failing to provide enough support to Gaza as US deadline passes

image.altText: Lightning strikes nearby a house in suburban australia during a storm

props.synopsis: Thunderstorms and torrential rain have hit across Australia this week, with forecasts suggesting this weather could continue through this week and to the end of the year.

title.children: Torrential rain hits Australia's east coast, with climate drivers activating thunderstorm season

image.altText: A digital board with multiple rows reading "cancelled".

props.synopsis: Jetstar, Qantas and Virgin Australia have cancelled flights to and from Bali until at least Wednesday afternoon.

title.children: Flights to and from Bali cancelled after volcanic eruption creates thick ash cloud

image.altText: Side photo of Queensland police car.

props.synopsis: A truck driver has been charged after two people lost their lives in the crash on the Bruce Highway near Rockhampton.

title.children: Truck driver charged after teenage boy and woman die in collision on Queensland highway

image.altText: A boy facing away from the camera in a hospital bed holds hand with a man with a beard.

props.synopsis: Muswellbrook has been rocked by more than 50 quakes since August that have damaged buildings, but some home owners have had their insurance claims rejected on the basis the issues were "pre-existing".

title.children: Homeowners hit by earthquake swarm question value of insurance after claims denied

image.altText: Samantha Harvey, a blonde woman in her 40s, holds up a book with artistic pictures of space on the cover.

props.synopsis: It takes 90 minutes for the International Space Station to orbit the Earth. That journey happens 16 times in Orbital, which just won one of the world's top literary awards.

title.children: 'There's nothing to do and there's everything to do': Novel set in space wins $98,000 Booker Prize

image.altText: A white woman with fair hair in a green t-shirt

props.synopsis: Advocacy groups have called for further reform of the Disability Support Pension and condemned the federal government for its response to a Senate inquiry into the payment.

title.children: Is the Disability Support Pension fit for purpose? Advocates say it needs a transformation

image.altText: A stressed-looking woman with short gray hair and maroon top sitting at a table with her head in her hand.

props.synopsis: First results of the 2024 National Carers Survey show many carers feel socially isolated and suffer from high or very high levels of psychological distress.

title.children: 'I've pretty much given up': Stressed and isolated carers say they can't get the support they need

image.altText: Tactical police officers stand on a roof in Weir Views.

props.synopsis: Police exchanged fire with an armed man at Weir Views in Melbourne's outer west on Tuesday, with the gunman locking himself into the home of an unsuspecting family.

title.children: Man caught in the crossfire of Melbourne police siege along with his infant son thanks his rescuers

image.altText: A Korean woman with short hair sitting at desk wearing Kodak yellow fleece.

props.synopsis: The radical feminist 4B movement took root in a culture where women face domestic violence and insidious spy-cam sexploitation, as well as the "double burden" of work and family.

title.children: Women in the US are joining a 'sex strike', but in Korea, 4B is a radical way of living

image.altText: A man on a bike rides through the street with ruins of buildings behind him

props.synopsis: Some 50,000 Russian troops have reportedly moved to a region held by Ukraine since August, with experts saying it is no coincidence that the renewed interest coincides with the US presidential race and the re-election of Donald Trump.

title.children: Russia wants Ukraine's 'bargaining chip' before Donald Trump returns to the White House

image.altText: Olaf Scholz wearing a navy suit standing in front of two microphones.

props.synopsis: The snap election was decided after the country's three-party coalition collapsed last week.

title.children: Germany to hold snap election in February after government's coalition collapse

image.altText: an aerial view of containers

props.synopsis: Multiple rounds of financial stimulus have slowed the pace of China's economic slowdown, but they've failed to help it reverse course.

title.children: Bailing out China's economy has suddenly become more urgent

image.altText: A PsiQuantum cryogenic cabinet

props.synopsis: Australian governments have been the big spender on quantum technology, outcompeting private capital. But a change in Queensland's government has put a question mark over that spending.

title.children: Governments outspend private sector in quantum race, as Australia chases emerging tech

image.altText: A robot that resembles a CCTV camera is attached to the front of a research vessel.

props.synopsis: Employees could be monitored at work or subjected to discrimination during recruitment if there is not appropriate oversight of artificial intelligence in the workplace, according to unions. But Australia's peak business body has cautioned against introducing further regulation that could prevent local businesses from having a "competitive edge".

title.children: Artificial intelligence could lead to workplace surveillance without further oversight, unions say

image.altText: A small child's hand is cupped by an old woman's hand

props.synopsis: One in three Australian grandparents babysit their grandkids to fill in gaps in childcare, becoming a support "village" for working parents, research finds. But what happens if you don't have grandparents to rely on?

title.children: What happens when you don't have a 'village' or grandparents to help with childcare?

image.altText: A composite image of the Rainbow Warrior, Rongelap Atoll and a nuclear explosion

props.synopsis: The Rainbow Warrior made headlines around the world when it was sunk by French operatives. But before that, its lesser-known last mission was to evacuate an entire island poisoned by nuclear testing in the Pacific.

title.children: US nuclear testing forced an entire island in the Pacific to evacuate — onboard a Greenpeace ship

image.altText: A collection of fresh shucked oysters.

props.synopsis: Australia's largest supplier of Sydney rock oysters is one of two producers targeted by thieves.

title.children: Thieves who stole up to 100,000 Sydney rock oysters could have industry ties, police suspect

image.altText: A canopy crane in a clearing in the Daintree rainforest

props.synopsis: James Cook Univeristy says its Daintree Rainforest research station is "severely under-utilised", even though the canopy crane is one of only six in the tropics worldwide.

title.children: Rainforest research station and rare 47m-high canopy crane face closure
